The lineage of Jesus Christ
The Gospel of Jesus Christ, Son of David, Son of Abraham:
Ibrahim was the son of Isaac. Isaac was the son of Jacob. Jacob was the son of Judah and his brothers.
And Judah begat Pharez and Zarah of Tamar. Pharez begat Hezron. And Hezron begat Aram.
And Aram begat Aminadab. And Aminadab begat Nahshon. And Nahshon begat Salmon.
And Salmon fathered Boaz of Rahab. And Boaz fathered Obed of Ruth. And Obed fathered Jesse.
And the son of David the king, and the son of Solomon to whom Uri the Hittite was father.
And Solomon the son of David. And David the son of Jesse.
And Asa was the son of Uzziah. Uzziah was the son of Joram. Joram was the son of Ahab.
And Uzziah fathered Jotham. Jotham fathered Ahaz. And Ahaz fathered Hezekiah.
And Hezekiah begat Manasseh. And Manasseh begat Amon. And Amon begat Josiah.
Yushia, son of Kenia, and his brothers were taken captive to Babylon.
And after the captivity of Babylon, Sheshai was born to Zerechiah. And Zerechiah was born to Abihail.
Zerah was the son of Pharez. Pharez was the son of Hezron. Hezron was the son of Perez.
Azor son of Sadoc. Sadoc son of Akim. Akim son of Eliod.
And Eliyahu was the son of Eliezer. And Eliezer was the son of Matthan. And Matthan was the son of Jacob.
And Joseph, the husband of Mary, of whom was born Jesus, who is called Christ.
For there were fourteen generations from Abraham to David, and fourteen from David to the captivity in Babylon, and fourteen from the captivity in Babylon to the Christ. The birth of Jesus Christ
The birth of Jesus Christ was as follows: when Mary, his mother, was betrothed to Joseph, before they came together, she was found with child of the Holy Spirit.
Joseph, her husband, was a good man, but he didn’t want to make a scene, so he wanted to leave her secretly.
But while he was considering these things, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream and said, “Joseph, son of David, do not be afraid to take to yourself Mary your wife, for that which is conceived in her is of the Holy Spirit.
“And she will bear a son, and you shall call his name Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins.”
And all this was, so that what was said by the Lord to the prophet might be fulfilled:
“Behold, the virgin shall be with child, and bear a son, and they shall call his name Immanuel”, which is to say: “God with us”.
When Joseph awoke from his sleep, he did as the angel of the Lord had commanded him; and he took his wife.
And he knew her until the birth of her firstborn son. And he called his name Jesus.
The Visit of the Magi
And when Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judaea in the days of King Herod, behold, magi from the east came to Jerusalem
They say: “Where is the child, the king of the Jews? For we have seen his star in the east and have come to worship him.”
When King Herod heard this, he and all Jerusalem were greatly troubled.
So he gathered all the chief priests and scribes of the people and asked them, “Where is the Christ born?”
They said to him, “In Bethlehem of Judah, for thus it is written by the prophet:
And you, Bethlehem, land of Judah, are by no means the least among the rulers of Judah, for out of you shall come a ruler who will shepherd my people Israel.
Then Herod privately summoned the wise men and learned from them the exact time of the star that had appeared.
Then he sent them to Bethlehem, and said, Go and search diligently for the young child; and when ye have found him, tell me that I may also go and worship him.
When they heard the king, they went away. And there was the star that they had seen in the east going before them, until it came and stood over where the young child was.
When they saw the star, they were very much delighted.
And they came to the house; and they saw the child with Mary his mother. And they fell down and worshipped him; and when they had opened their treasures, they presented unto him gifts; gold and incense and myrrh.
Then it was revealed to them in a dream not to return to Herod, and they departed to their own country. Flight to Egypt
And when they had departed, behold, the angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream, saying, “Arise, take the young man and his mother, and flee into Egypt, and be there until I tell you; for Herod is about to search for the child, to destroy him.”
He got up, took the boy and his mother at night and went to Egypt.
And there was until the death of Herod, in order to be fulfilled what was said by the Lord through the prophet who said: “From Egypt I called my son.”
Then Herod, when he saw that the wise men had mocked him, was exceedingly angry; and he sent and slew all the young children that were in Bethlehem, and in all the coasts thereof, from two years old and under, according to the time which he had diligently inquired of the wise men.
Then was done what was said by the prophet Jeremiah, who said:
«A voice was heard in the wilderness, the voice of one crying. Bereavement and mourning, wailing and sorrow. Rachel weeps for her children; she desires no comfort, for they are no more». Return to Nazareth
When Herod died, an angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream in Egypt
“Arise, take the boy and his mother, and go to the land of Israel, for those who were seeking the boy’s life are dead.”
He got up, took the boy and his mother and came to the land of Israel.
But when he heard that Archelaus ruled over Judea instead of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there. And he was divinely inspired in a dream to go to the district of Galilee.
And he came and dwelt in a city called Nazareth, that it might be fulfilled which was spoken of the prophets, He shall be called a Nazarenes.
John the Baptist Prepares the Way
In those days came John the Baptist and preached in the wilderness of Judea.
“Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand.”
This is what is said of him in the Book of Isaiah, the prophet who said: “A voice cries out in the wilderness: Prepare the way of the Lord, make straight his paths.”
And this John wore a garment of camel’s hair, and a leather girdle about his loins; and his meat was locusts and wild honey.
Then came to him Jerusalem with all the Jews throughout all the region that lay beyond the Jordan,
And they were confirmed in Jordan, acknowledging their sins.
When many of the Pharisees and Sadducees came to his baptism, they said to him, “Teacher, we are descending from John to you!”
Make fruits befitting for repentance.
And do not think that you can say, ‘We have Abraham as our father.’ For I tell you that out of these stones God is able to raise up children for Abraham.
Now the axe has been laid to the root of the tree; every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire.
I baptize you with water for repentance, but he who comes after me is mightier than I, and I am not worthy to carry his shoes. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire.
“He who sows in the summer shall have a double harvest. He who treads in the spring shall have a good harvest; but he who sows in the autumn shall have only a poor harvest, even if he treads as in the other seasons.” The baptism of Jesus Christ
Then Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan to John, to be baptized by him.
But John stopped him, saying: “I need to be baptized by you, and are you coming to me?”
Jesus answered and said to him, “Allow it now, for in this manner it is right for us to fulfill all righteousness.” Then he allowed him.
When Jesus was baptized, he came up immediately from the water, and behold, the heavens were opened to him, and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and coming upon him.
And a voice came from heaven, saying, “This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased.”
Jesus Confronts Temptation
Then Jesus was led up by the Spirit in the wilderness to be tempted by the devil.
After fasting for forty days and forty nights, he finally got hungry.
The sorcerer came to him and said: “If you are the son of God, say that these stones become bread.”
He answered and said: “It is written: ‘Man does not live by bread alone, but by every word that comes from the mouth of God.’”
Then Satan took him to the holy city, and set him on the edge of the temple,
And he said to him, “If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down, for it is written that he commands the angels concerning you, and they will bear you up in their hands, lest you strike your foot against a stone.”
Jesus said to him: “It is also written: ‘Do not put the Lord your God to the test.’”
Then Satan also took him to a very high mountain, and showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory,
And he said to him, “I will give you all this if you get down on your knees and worship me.”
Then Jesus said to him, “Get out of me, Satan! For it is written, ‘Worship the Lord your God, and serve only him.’”
Then Satan left him, and lo, angels came and ministered unto him. The beginning of his ministry in Galilee
When Jesus heard that John had been imprisoned, he withdrew to Galilee.
And he left Nazareth and came and dwelt in Capernaum, which is by the sea, in the borders of Zabulon and Naphtali;
So that what is said by the prophet Isaiah may be fulfilled:
The land of Zebulun, and the land of Naphtali, and the path of the sea, beyond Jordan, the land of the Gentiles.
“The people who were sitting in the darkness saw a great light, and the people who were sitting in the circle of death and its shadows a light has shone upon them.”
From that time Jesus began to preach, and to say, “Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand.” The First Call of the Disciples
As Jesus was walking by the Sea of Galilee, he saw two brothers: Simon, who was called Peter, and Andrew, his brother. They were casting a net into the sea, for they were fishermen.
He said to them, “Follow me, and I will make you fishers of men.”
They left the net and followed him.
Then he went on and saw two other brothers, James and John, the sons of Zebedee, in the boat with their father Zebedee mending their nets, and he called them.
They left the ship and their father, and followed him. Jesus teaches and heals the sick
And Jesus was going through all Galilee, teaching in their synagogues, proclaiming the good news of the kingdom, and healing every disease and every weakness in the people.
His fame spread throughout Syria. So they brought to him all the sick with various diseases and pains, and the mad and the convulsed and the paralyzed, and he healed them.
And great multitudes followed him from Galilee and the Decapolis and Jerusalem and Judea and beyond the Jordan.
The Sermon on the Mount - The Beatitudes
And when the crowds saw it, they went up on the mountain; and when he sat down, his disciples came to him.
He opened his mouth and taught them.
“Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.”
Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth.
Blessed are those who are hungry and thirsty for righteousness, for they will be filled.
Blessed are the merciful, for they shall be merciful.
Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called the children of God.
Blessed are those who are persecuted for righteousness’ sake, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are you when they revile you and persecute you and utter all kinds of evil against you, lying because of me.
Rejoice and be glad, for your reward is great in heaven, for in the same way they persecuted the prophets who were before you. Salt of the earth and light of the world
“You are the salt of the earth, but if the salt has become tasteless, with what can it be seasoned? It is no longer good for anything, except to be thrown out and trodden under foot by people.”
You are the light of the world. A city set on a hill cannot be hidden,
They do not light a lamp and put it under a measure, but on a lampstand it gives light to all who are in the house.
Let your light so shine before men, that they may see your good works, and glorify your Father which is in heaven. The Fulfilment of the Law
“Do not think that I have come to destroy the law or the prophets. I have not come to destroy but to fulfill.”
I tell you the truth, until heaven and earth pass away, not one tittle, not one stroke, will pass from the law until all is accomplished.
Whoever breaks one of these least commandments and teaches people so, will be called least in the kingdom of heaven. But whoever does and teaches, that will be called great in the kingdom of heaven.
I say to you that unless your righteousness exceeds that of the scribes and Pharisees, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven.
“You have heard that it was said, ‘Do not commit murder, and whoever commits murder is subject to judgment.’
And I say to you: whoever is angry with his brother without cause shall be in danger of judgment; and whoever says to his brother: “Raca,” shall be in danger of the council; and whoever says: “You fool!” shall be in danger of hell fire.
If you present your offering at the altar, and there you remember that you have something against your brother,
Leave your offering before the altar, and go first and make peace with your brother, and then come and present your offering.
Be content with your opponent quickly as long as you are on the same road, lest the opponent hand you over to the judge, and the judge hand you over to the policeman, and you are imprisoned.
I tell you the truth: don’t leave there until you’ve paid the last penny! Adultery
“You have heard that it was said, ‘Do not commit adultery.’
But I say to you that everyone who looks at a woman to lust for her has committed adultery with her already in his heart.
If the right eye causes you to stumble, pluck it out and cast it from you, for it is better for you that one of your members perishes and your whole body is cast into hell.
If your right hand causes you to sin, cut it off and throw it from you, for it is better for you that one of your members perishes than your whole body be thrown into hell. Divorce
“And it was said: whoever divorces his wife, let him give her a letter of divorce.”
And I say to you: whoever divorces his wife, except for unchastity, makes her an adulteress; and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery.
“You have also heard that it was said to the people in former times: ‘Do not break your word; but keep your engagements to the Lord.’
And I say to you: Do not swear at all, not by heaven, for it is God’s throne,
And neither is he in the earth, because he walketh among his people.
And do not swear by your head, because you cannot make one hair white or black.
But let your speech be: Yes, yes; no, no. Whatever is beyond that is of the evil one. Revenge
“You have heard that it was said: ‘An eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth.’
And I say to you: Do not resist evil, but whoever slaps you on your right cheek, turn the other also to him.
And whoever wants to sue you and take your coat, let him have the cloak also.
And whoever makes you laugh for one mile, go with him for two.
Give to everyone who asks you, and if anyone wants to borrow from you, do not turn him away. Love your enemies
“You have heard that it was said, ‘Love your neighbor and hate your enemy.’
But I say to you: Love your enemies. Bless those who curse you, do good to those who hate you, and pray for those who spitefully treat you and persecute you,
That you may be sons of your Father who is in heaven; for He makes His sun rise on the evil and on the good, and sends rain on the just and on the unjust.
For if you love those who love you, what reward have you? Do not even the tax collectors do that?
And if you only greet your brothers, what good are you doing? Are not the tithers also doing this?
Be ye therefore perfect, even as your Father which is in heaven is perfect.
Charity
“Beware of making your righteousness before men, to be seen by them; otherwise you have no reward with your Father who is in heaven.”
When you make a charity, do not sound the trumpet before you, as the hypocrites do in the marketplaces and in the alleys, in order to be glorified by the people. I tell you the truth: they have received their reward!
And when you do charity, then you do not know what your right hand has done with your left hand.
So that your deed may be secret. Your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly. The prayer
«And when you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, for they love to pray standing in the synagogues and at the street corners, that they may be seen by men. I tell you the truth, they have received their reward.
And when you pray, go into your closet and shut the door and pray to your Father who is in secret; and your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly.
And when you come, do not repeat empty talk like the nations, for they think that by the multitude of their words they will be heard.
Do not be like them. For your Father knows what you need before you ask him.
“This is how you should pray: ‘Our Father in heaven, hallowed be your name.’”
Let Your kingdom come. Let Your will be done, on earth, as it is in heaven.
Our daily bread give us this day.
And forgive us our sins as we also forgive the sinners to us.
And lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from the evil one. For thine is the kingdom, and the power, and the glory, for ever. Amen.
For if ye forgive men their trespasses, your heavenly Father will also forgive you.
If you do not forgive people their trespasses, neither will your Father in heaven forgive your trespasses. Fasting
«When you fast, do not put on a sad expression like the hypocrites, for they disfigure their faces so that people will see that they are fasting. I tell you the truth, they have received their reward.
And you, when you fast, anoint your head and wash your face,
So that you may not appear to men to be fasting, but to your Father who is in secret. For your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly. Treasures in heaven
“Do not lay up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moth and rust consume and where thieves break in and steal.
But lay up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust destroys, and where thieves do not dig and steal.
For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.
The lamp of the body is the eye; if therefore the eye be in you, your whole body will be full of light.
If your eye is evil, your whole body is full of darkness; and if the light that is in you is darkness, how great is the darkness!
«No one can serve two masters, for either he will hate the one and love the other, or he will be devoted to the one and despise the other. You cannot serve both God and money. God takes care of us.
“Therefore I say to you, do not worry about your life, what you will eat or what you will drink, nor about your body, what you will put on. Is life not worth more than food, and the body than clothes?
Look at the birds of the air: they neither sow nor reap nor gather into barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not worth much more than they?
And who of you, if he is attentive, can add to his stature an arm?
And why are you worried about clothing? Consider the lilies of the field how they grow; they toil not, neither do they spin.
But I say to you that not even Solomon in all his glory was dressed like one of these.
If the grass of the field which is today and is thrown tomorrow in the furnace, God clothes it like this, is it not more reasonable that He clothes you, you of little faith?
Do not worry, saying, “What shall we eat?” or “What shall we drink?” or “What shall we wear?”
For such things do nations ask of their gods. For your heavenly Father knows that you need all these things.
But seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness, and all these things shall be added to you.
Do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will worry about itself. Sufficient for the day is its own trouble.
The Art of Blaming Others
“Do not judge, that you yourselves may not be judged,
For by the judgment by which you judge you will be judged, and by the measure by which you measure it will be measured to you.
Why do you notice the speck in your brother’s eye, but are not mindful of the log in your own eye?
Or how would you say to your brother: Let me take the splinters out of your eye, while there is a log in your eye?
You hypocrite, first get the log out of your own eye, and then you will see clearly how to take the speck out of your brother’s eye!
Do not give Jerusalem to the dogs, and do not throw your pearls before swine, lest they trample them under their feet and turn and tear you to pieces. Ask, seek, knock
“Ask and it will be given you; seek and you will find; knock and the door will be opened to you.”
For whoever asks receives, and whoever seeks finds, and to whoever knocks it will be opened.
Can any of you, if his son asks for bread, give him a stone?
If he is asked by a fish, will he give it alive?
If you, being evil, know how to give your children good gifts, how much more will your Father who is in heaven give good things to those who ask him!
Do to others whatever you would like them to do to you, for this is the law and the prophets. The Narrow Gate
“Enter by the narrow gate; for wide is the gate and broad is the road that leads to destruction, and many are those who enter by it!
How narrow the gate and how difficult the road that leads to life! Only a few find it! The tree and its fruit
“Beware of false prophets who come to you in sheep’s clothing but inwardly are ravenous wolves!”
By their fruits you shall know them. Do they pick grapes from thorns, or figs from thistles?
So every good tree bears good fruit, and a bad tree bears bad fruit;
A good tree cannot make bad fruit, nor a bad tree make good fruit.
Every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire.
So you will know them by their fruits.
“Not everyone who says to me, ‘Lord, Lord,’ will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven.
Many will say to me on that day, ‘Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name, and in your name drive out demons, and in your name perform many deeds of power?’
Then I will say to them, ‘I never knew you! Depart from me, you workers of iniquity!’ The wise builders and the foolish builders
“Whoever hears these words of mine and acts on them, he is like a sensible man, who built his house on rock.”
The rain came down, the streams rose, and the winds blew and beat against the house; yet it did not fall, because it was founded on the rock.
And whoever hears my words and does not act on them, is like a foolish man who built his house on sand.
"The rain came down, the rivers came, the winds blew, and the house fell over. And it fell with a great crash!"
When Jesus had finished these sayings, the crowds were astonished at his teaching.
For he was teaching them as one having authority, and not as the scribes.
The Healing of the Leper
And when he came down from the mountain, great crowds followed him.
And if the leper came and fell on his face and said: “Lord, if you will, you can make me clean.”
And Jesus stretched out his hand and touched him, saying, “I want to, be clean!” And immediately his leprosy was cleansed.
Jesus said to him, “See that you say nothing to anyone. But go, show yourself to the priest and offer the sacrifice that Moses commanded, a testimony to them.” The faith of the centurion
And when Jesus came into Capernaum, a centurion came to him
And he says: “O Lord, my servant is paralyzed and in great pain in the house.”
Jesus said to him, “I am coming and will heal him.”
Then the captain answered and said, “Sir, I am not worthy that you should enter under my roof; but say the word, and my servant shall be healed.
“For verily I am a man under authority. I have soldiers under my command. I say to one: Go! And he goes. To another: Come! And he comes. To my servant: Do this! And he does it.”
When Jesus heard this, he was amazed at him and said to those who were following him, “I tell you the truth, I have not found such great faith even in Israel!”
And I say to you: many will come from the east and the west, and will take their place with Abraham and Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven,
“And the children of the kingdom shall be cast into outer darkness; there shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth.”
Then Jesus said to the centurion, “Go, let it be done for you as you believed.” And he was healed at that very hour. Healing of Peter’s mother-in-law and others
And when Jesus came to Peter’s house, he saw Peter’s mother-in-law lying in a fever,
He touched her hand and the fever left her, so she got up and served them.
And when evening came, many who were crazy were brought to him, and he cast out the spirits by a word, and cured all the sick.
In order for what is said in the prophet Isaiah to come true: “He took our sicknesses and carried our diseases.” The price of dependency
And when Jesus saw such a great multitude about him, he commanded Peter to go a little apart into the sea.
A writer came forward and said, “Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go.”
Jesus said to him, “The foxes have holes and the birds of the air have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head.”
And one of his disciples said to him, “Lord, let me go first and bury my father.”
Jesus said to him, “Follow me, and let the dead bury their own dead.”
And when he entered the ship, his disciples followed him.
And a great disturbance occurred in the sea until the waves covered the ship, and he was sleeping.
His disciples came forward and woke him, saying, “Lord, save us, for we are perishing!”
He said to them, “What makes you afraid, O you of little faith?” Then he stood up, rebuked the wind and the waves, and there was a great calm.
The people wondered, saying, “Who is this man? For even the winds and the sea obey him!” The casting out of devils
And when he came to the border of the land of the Gerasenes, two demoniacs coming out of the tombs met him, so full of madness that no one could pass that way.
And when they cried out, “What have we to do with thee, Jesus the Son of God? art thou come here before the time to afflict us?”
And there was a great company of swine feeding at a distance.
The devils asked him, saying, “If you can drive us out, let us go to the pigs.”
He said to them, “Go!” So they went and came to the pigsty, and the whole herd of pigs rushed down from the bank into the sea, and they died in the water.
The shepherds fled and went to the city, and told everything, and about the two madmen.
So the whole city went out to meet Jesus. When they saw him, they asked him to leave their neighborhood.
Curing Paralysis
He entered the ship and passed by and came to his city.
And if a paralytic is brought to him lying on a bed. When Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic, “Son, your sins are forgiven.”
And if some of the scribes had said to themselves: “This one is blaspheming!”
Now Jesus knew their thoughts, and said to them, “Why are you thinking this in your hearts?
It is easier to say: "Your sins are forgiven", than to say: "Get up and walk"?
But that you may know that the Son of man hath power on earth to forgive sins.” And he saith to the paralytic, “Rise, take up thy bed, and go unto thine house.”
He got up and went to his house.
When the crowds saw it, they were amazed and glorified God, who had given such authority to men. Matthew
As he went on his way, he saw a man sitting by the collection-box, and he said to him, “Follow me.” He got up and followed him.
While he was in the house, many tax collectors and sinners came and sat with Jesus and his disciples.
When the Pharisees saw this, they said to his disciples, “Why does your teacher eat with tax collectors and sinners?”
When he heard this, Jesus said to them, “Those who are well do not need a doctor but the sick.”
Go and learn what it is: “I desire mercy, not sacrifice, for I have not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance.” The question about fasting
Then his disciples came to him, saying, “Why do we and the Pharisees fast much, but your disciples do not fast?”
Jesus said to them, “Can the friends of the bridegroom fast while the bridegroom is with them? But there will come a time when the bridegroom is taken away from them, and then they will fast.”
No one puts a new piece of cloth on an old garment, for the new piece will take from the old, and the old will be torn apart.
They do not put new wine into old bottles, or else the bottles would burst. The wine would spill and the bottles would break. But they put new wine into new bottles, and so both are preserved.” The healing of the daughter of Jairus and the woman with the issue of blood
And while he was saying this to them, behold, the chief came, and bowed himself to him, saying, “My daughter is dead now, but come and lay your hand on her, and she will live.”
Then Jesus rose, and with him Peter and his disciples.
And a woman who had been bleeding for twelve years came up behind him and touched the hem of his garment.
For she said within herself, If I may but touch his garment, I shall be made well.
Jesus looked around and saw her, and said, “Have faith, daughter. Your faith has made you well.” And at that moment she was made well.
And when Jesus came into the chief’s house, and beheld the noise of the multitude and the tumult,
He said to them, “Get out of the way, the children are not dead but asleep.” They laughed at him.
When he had dismissed the assembly, he took her by the hand, and she stood up.
And the news of it went throughout the whole of that land. Healing of the blind
As he went on his way, Jesus heard them calling out, “Have mercy on us, Son of David!”
When he came to the house, blind men came to him, and he said to them, “Do you believe that I can do this?” They said to him, “Yes, Lord!”
Then he touched their eyes and said to them, “According to your faith let it be done to you.”
Their eyes were opened. Jesus rebuked them, saying, “Look, so that no one may know!”
But they went out and spread the word about it throughout all that land. The healing of the mute
As they were going out, another mute, mad man was brought to him.
When the devil was cast out, the dumb man spoke, and the crowd was amazed, saying, “Never has anything like this been seen in Israel!”
The Pharisees said, “By the prince of the demons he drives out the demons!” But few do the deeds.
And Jesus went about all the cities and villages, teaching in their synagogues, and preaching the gospel of the kingdom, and healing every sickness and every infirmity.
And when the crowds saw them, they were moved with compassion for them, for they were like sheep without a shepherd.
Then he said to his disciples: “The harvest is plentiful, but the workers are few.
“Seek from the Lord of the harvest to send a worker to his harvest.”
Dispatch the twelve
Then he called his twelve disciples to him and gave them authority over unclean spirits, so that they might cast them out and cure every disease and every weakness.
